author: logicsoup
body: All these graphs contain accurate data points, but the data has just been presented misleadingly. #politics #statistics #graph #biden #leftist #viral
stickers:
Debunking misleading graphs First up, we have this pretty famous graph from Fox News. It looks like the top tax rate is going to increase massively, right? But if you look at the scale, youâ€™ll see that it doesnâ€™t start at 0, and itâ€™s been made smaller than you would expect. Itâ€™s actually a 4.6% increase. Same problem as this graph, where women from Latvia are made out to be way taller than everyone else. If you look at the scale, the data points are inches from each other. Next is this graph, which is accurate, but misleading. You might think Florida is a much more dangerous place to swim than the other states here. In reality, this graph doesnâ€™t account for the fact that Florida has a longer coastline than the other states. Next is this graph, which makes it look as though people who are over the age of 60 are not disproportionately affected by coronavirus. The problem is that the age categories are uneven. Every single person between the age of 18 and 59 has been lumped together in one category, so of course that category would be bigger than the others. This graph has a problem with its scale too, but not in the same way as the other graphs before. Instead of being too small, itâ€™s too big, making it seem as though global temperatures have not been increasing in the past century. The massive scale is innapropriate here since just one degree has a huge impact. This is the correct version, and like for Part 2!

body: Reply to @the_matrix_agent_smith The Achilles tendon of our brain #STEM #cognitive #todayilearned #statistics
stickers:
Whatâ€™s shakinâ€™ bacon! In case you didnâ€™t know, 
our brains are kind of terrible at understanding Just how big some numbers really are  And to demonstrate this 
I need you to picture something for me How long do you think 
one million seconds is? Could be hours, days, years, etc. Now think about 
one billion seconds and then one trillion seconds 1 million seconds = 11 1/2 days 1 billion seconds =  ~32 years 1 trillion seconds = ~31,000 years! One theory behind 
this is that from an 
evolutionary perspective  There was no benefit 
nor necessity for us  To comprehend numbers 
of that magnitude Our inability to fathom large numbers is a setback But I think that being aware of that cognitive weakness is actually a great way  To challenge your assumptions and strengthen your perspective

Remember the game Plinko? cc: Same idea. Each ball bounces off a peg & goes either left or right. And as they travel down they keep bouncing left or right until they reach the bins belowï¿¼ï¿¼ï¿¼ï¿¼ï¿¼ cc: Now, that little pyramid overlaying the pegs is Pascalâ€™s Triangle and it shows the total number of possible pathways to reach that bin cc: Notice the 1 down the sides? That means thereâ€™s only one possible pathway that the beads could take to get to those binsï¿¼ï¿¼ cc: to get to the leftmost bin a bead would have to bounce left, then left again, then left again, thenâ€”you get the idea cc: and in statistics the more sample data you have, the more the sample means, or beads, tend to approximate the normal curve, seen here. body: Refuting the â€œtalk to someone whoâ€™s lived under com*unism!â€ argument #fyp #foryou #leftist #leftism #statistics #socialism #politics #anecdote
stickers: CC: So one of the most frequent responses I get being pro-com*unism is â€œTalk to someone whoâ€™s lived under com*unism and see what they have to say about it. To which I would simply have to say, â€œAnecdotes are not data.â€ And mass polling from the last decade has shown time and again that the majority of people who did live in nations that were attempting to build com*unism, wish they could go back. Hereâ€™s a list of polls right here: Russia, USSR: https://www.levada.ru/2018/12/19/nostalgiya-po-sssr-2/ Spiegel, East Germany: https://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/homesick-for-a-dictatorship-majority-of-eastern-germans-feel-life-better-under-communism-a-634122.html Balkan Insight, Serbia: https://balkaninsight.com/2010/12/24/for-simon-poll-serbians-unsure-who-runs-their-country/ Romania Libera: https://romanialibera.ro/actualitate/eveniment/sondaj--53--dintre-romani-s-ar-intoarce-la-comunism-273175 Reuters, Easter Europe: https://www.reuters.com/article/us-communism-nostalgia-idUSTRE5A701320091108 Pew Research Center, Hungary: https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2010/04/28/hungary-better-off-under-communism/ And data and statistics as a result of mass polling will always beat out individual stories. Additionally, if someone already had the financial means to not only leave their country move somewhere else But the cultural mindset to adapt to new life there, they were probably already in a position of relative privilege from where they came from. And a lot of these people that I hear talk about how bad communism was are very, very pro-capitalist. All your anecdote tells me, is about your individual experience. It doesnâ€™t tell me com*unism is bad.

stickers:
How to Lie with Statistics Iâ€™ve talked about ways statistics can be misleading in my last few videos, but I havenâ€™t talked about the number one fallacy associated with statistics - and thatâ€™s the post hoc fallacy. So letâ€™s talk about it PART 5 Most people know that â€œcorrelation doesnâ€™t equal causationâ€ but not necessarily why, so Iâ€™m going to outline three reasons why this might be the case and give an example for each. Number 1, there could be a lurking variable. For example, this graph might lead you to conclude that ice cream sales cause shark attacks because theyâ€™re both strongly correlated. But the reason why theyâ€™re correlated isnâ€™t because one caused the other, instead itâ€™s because of a lurking variable. A lurking variable is a third factor which causes both. In this case itâ€™s the weather. When itâ€™s hot, people want ice cream as a tasty snack. But the hot weather also makes people 
want to go out for a swim in the sea, meaning theyâ€™re more likely to become a sharkâ€™s tasty snack. The second reason why correlation might not equal causation is because one of the trends is universal. So for example, â€œEveryone who has gone to the moon has drunk water. Therefore, drinking water makes you go to the moon.â€ This doesnâ€™t work, because everyone has drunk water. Thirdly, the two events might be a coincidence. So for example, just becauseI ate bread yesterday and I have a cold today doesnâ€™t mean that the bread caused the cold. Mayhe they have nothing to do with each another. To get around this, well-conducted studies will use a large sample size.
